        <div class="story">
          <h5>His Story</h5>
          <p>
            My first impressions of Ingrid when we first met in 2011 were not good ones. She was overly bubbly and loud, and I think she accidentally threw a football into a nearby pond.
          </p>
          <p>
            To this day, she’s still overly bubbly, loud, and somewhat clumsy. But, in the last 5.5 years, I’ve also come to fully understand just how lucky and blessed I am to be with a passionate, deeply caring, and overall wonderful human being like Ingrid.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ingrid and I got to know each other better during the summer of 2013. During that time, I was drawn to her genuine warmth and her “down for whatever” spontaneity. I started to <i>like</i> like her, but also knew that the chances of anything beyond friendship was slim because I was about to move to Fort Worth to teach, while she still had 2 more years of school left in Austin.
          </p>
          <p>
            Towards the end of that summer though, we decided to give long-distance relationship a shot. On July 6th of 2013, we shot fireworks together, and I asked Ingrid to be my girlfriend.
          </p>
          <p>
            Since that moment, so much has changed: we’ve lived in multiple different cities, raised several puppies together, changed careers, and both grown and changed in many ways. Through it all,  Ingrid has been the one constant. 
          </p>
          <p>
            She’s been a constant thorn in my side who knows just how to perfectly irritate me with her affinity for Naruto running, her obnoxious cackling, and her uncanny ability to come up with horrifyingly embarrassing cutesy nicknames for me. She’s also been a constant source of joy, strength, and love, especially through some of my darkest and loneliest times.
          </p>
          <p>
            And so, earlier this year, I bought a ring, accidentally texted a picture of it to her, waited for 2 months in hopes that the memory of me accidentally texting her a picture of her engagement ring might somewhat fade away from her mind, and then finally asked her to be my wife. Wahoo!
          </p>
